text:
Harlem Market, between First Ave. and the East River, from 102nd to 105th Streets. This market probably does more vegetable business than any other open air market in the world, in being one of the sources of food supply in New York City.

About 1923.

Ewing Galloway.
title: Occupations - Peddlers - Food - Vegetables.

text:
East 102nd Street, north side, east from, but not including First Ave., to the Harlem River. The Harlem Farmers Square, is at the rear of buildings shown.

September 21, 1930.

P. L. Sperr.

1-East 102nd Street, west side, at corner looking west from southeast corner of First Avenue.

P. L. Sperr
